works.title: Creativity in Computer Science and Fiction Writing
works.description: This paper compares the creative processes of fiction writers and computer scientists, highlighting that fiction offers more freedom, while computer science is more logic-driven. Despite differences, both fields involve creativity.

works.title: Effective Manipulation Through Music
works.description: The paper discusses how music effectively manipulates others in various contexts such as the workplace, advertising, and torture, while also offering counter-arguments for a balanced view.

works.title: The Ethical and Social Consequences of Direct-to-Consumer Genetic Testing
works.description: This paper explores the ethical and social consequences of Direct-to-Consumer (DTC) genetic testing, highlighting concerns about medical principles such as autonomy, beneficence, and justice.

works.title: The Nano Revolution Mirrors the Industrial Revolution: Who Will Benefit From the Nano Revolution?
works.description: This paper compares the Nano Revolution to the Industrial Revolution, exploring how nanotechnology will redefine robots and impact various fields, including biotechnology.

works.title: The Ethics of Accountability in Factory Farming
works.description: This paper explores the ethical responsibility of corporations, farmers, consumers, and government officials in factory farming, advocating for greater awareness of their roles in animal welfare and meat production.

works.title: Vintage: Wearing the Present in the Past
works.description: This paper explores how vintage clothing in modern fashion enables individuality, nostalgia, and creative expression, while allowing for innovative yet familiar styles.

works.title: What's So Funny? The Real World Impact of Sitcom Depictions of Class
works.description: This paper critiques situational comedies that satirize working-class families, highlighting their reinforcement of negative stereotypes and the undermining of upward mobility.

works.title: Taboo the Taboos: The Ethics of Food Waste
works.description: This paper examines the origins of food waste, focusing on food taboos, dumpster diving ethics, and the need to challenge societal norms to reduce waste and address food insecurity.

works.title: The Fast Food Industry's Role in the Rising Rate of Obesity Among People of Low Socioeconomic Status
works.description: This paper explores the fast food industry's role in rising obesity rates among low-income individuals, emphasizing the impact of economic and environmental factors.

works.title: Hip Hop's Masked Authenticity
works.description: This paper explores the complex concept of authenticity in hip hop, examining how race, gender, and cultural ties influence the perception of 'realness' in rap music.

works.title: The Impact of Shiftwork on the Everyday Worker
works.description: This paper examines the negative impacts of night shift work on individual health, well-being, and work-life balance, as well as its effects on companies.

works.title: The Narrative Power of Photography: Two Paragraphs and “The Limits of Forgiveness”
works.description: This paper explores the power of photography to shape narratives, particularly in historical contexts, and examines how past images of injustice can have a stronger emotional impact than modern staged photos.

works.title: Pediatric Cadmium Toxicity in America: Exploring Everyday Exposure Risk for Cavities and Decreased Neurodevelopment
works.description: This paper examines the health risks of cadmium in children's products, focusing on its presence in toys and jewelry, and the lack of regulation despite public outcry.

works.title: The Autism Epidemic
works.description: This paper challenges the use of the term 'epidemic' to describe the rise in autism spectrum disorder cases, attributing the increase to better diagnosis, awareness, and expanded criteria.
